Exploring the Bay Wheels (Lyft) Bike Dataset for August 2021¶

by Elaine Chow¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset that contains individual rides in August 2021 from a bike-sharing system run by Lyft called Bay Wheels.

Some Background on Bay Wheels (from www.lyft.com/bikes/bay-wheels)¶

Bay Wheels bikes are found at more than 400 stations in San Francisco, the East Bay (Oakland, Berkeley and Emeryville) and San Jose. A station is the row of docked bikes; a dock is what holds each individual bicycle.

Bay Wheels offers two kinds of bikes: hybrid electric bikes, which have a battery, and "classic" bikes, which are rider-powered.

There are two kinds of riders: annual or monthly members, and casual riders who either pay by the single ride or who purchase an access pass (which allows unlimited 30-minute rides over a 24 hour period).

In August 2021, the fees were as follows:

  • For a casual rider, a single ride starts at \$3 for the first 30 minutes. If the single ride is on an ebike, there is an extra fee of 0.20 per minute.
  • An Access Pass is \$10 for a classic bike; an additional 0.30 per minute is charged for ebikes. According Lyft, the Access Pass is popular with tourists.
  • Annual memberships are \$159/year and include unlimited 45-minute classic bike rides.
  • Monthly memberships are \$25/month and include unlimited 45-minute classic bike rides for 30 days from purchase.
  • Members who ride an ebike pay 0.15 per minute during the included ride time.
  • Non-member or casual riders pay \$3 for every 15 minutes after the 30-minute ride time has expired.
  • Members who ride a classic bike pay \$2 for every 15 minutes after 45 minutes have expired.

The maximum bike rental period is 24 hours; Lyft warns that for bikes kept for more than 24 hours, "you may be charged a lost or stolen bike fee of \$1,200 (plus tax)."

Bay Wheels bikes may be ridden outside the service area, but a rider can end a trip only as follows:

  • Classic bikes can only be returned to any station with an open dock.
  • Electric bikes can be returned to any Bay Wheels station or locked to any public bike rack within the service area. Parking an ebike at a bike rack, instead of docking at a Bay Wheels station, will cost an additional \$2 for members and casual riders.

To expand our analysis, we'll need the calculate the time duration of rides. To facilitate my analysis of the time duration of rides, I converted the started_at and ended_at values to datetime objects and then created a new column, "ride_duration", which is the time duration in minutes.¶

In [55]:
#convert "started_at" to datetime object
from datetime import datetime

df_clean['started_at'] = df_clean['started_at'].apply(lambda x: datetime.strptime(x, '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S'))
In [56]:
#convert "ended_at" to datetime object
df_clean['ended_at'] = df_clean['ended_at'].apply(lambda x: datetime.strptime(x, '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S'))
In [57]:
#create a new column, "ride_duration", which is the difference in minutes 
#between ended_at and started_at
from dateutil.relativedelta import relativedelta
from datetime import date

#calculate the difference in minutes between when a ride started and when it ended.
df_clean["ride_duration"] = df_clean['ended_at'] - df_clean['started_at']
df_clean["ride_duration"]=df_clean["ride_duration"]/np.timedelta64(1,'m')

Given the large number of start station and end names where the value is "Unavailable," I won't be analyzing the start (or end station data) and will be calculating distance in kilometers between starting and ending latitude/longitude points to get a sense of possible ride distances, knowing that in some cases riders will return the bike to where they started.¶

I decided to apply the Haversine formula to calculate the distance in kilometers between two sets of latitude/longitude points. It obviously will not map the route that was actually traveled, but will give a rough idea of the kind of distances that riders will ride Bay Wheels. More on the Haversine formula can be found here:¶

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haversine_formula

In [95]:
#a function that calculates the Haversine formula
def haversine(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2, to_radians=True, earth_radius=6371):
    if to_radians:
        lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2 = np.radians([lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2])

    a = np.sin((lat2-lat1)/2.0)**2 + \
        np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin((lon2-lon1)/2.0)**2

    return earth_radius * 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))

Given that we have a rough idea of the pricing scheme for Bay Wheels, we are going to estimate the cost for each ride. Because we can't tell if an electric bike is parked outside of the service area, we will not be applying the \$25 service fee, but if a bike's end_station_name is "Unavailable," we will be applying the \\$2 fee for not docking the bike at the end of the ride. Also, we don't know if a member if a monthly or annual member, so we will not be calculating any membership costs into a ride.¶

In [99]:
#create a function, calculate, that calculates the cost for a ride, depending on the type of rider, the type of bike,
# the duration of the ride and whether the bike was docked at a station at the end of a ride if it was an electric bike.
import math
def calculate(ride_duration, bike_type, membership, end_station_name):
    cost = 0
    duration = round(ride_duration, 0)   
    if membership=="member":  #if rider is a member
        if (bike_type=="classic_bike"): #if bike is classic
            if duration <= 45:
                cost = 0
            else:
                cost = math.ceil((duration-45)/15)*2
        elif bike_type=="electric_bike": #if bike is electric
            cost = duration*(0.15)
            if end_station_name == "Unavailable": #if electric bike not docked at end of ride
                cost = cost + 2
    elif membership == "casual": #if rider is casual
        if bike_type =="classic_bike":
            if duration <= 30:
                cost = 3.0
            else:
                cost = 3.0 + math.ceil((duration-30)/15)*3
        elif bike_type == "docked_bike": #if bike is docked, assume Access Pass was purchased for $10
            cost = 10.0
        elif bike_type == "electric_bike": #if bike is electric
            cost = 3+ duration*(0.20)
            if end_station_name == "Unavailable": #if electric bike not docked at end of ride
                cost = cost+2
    return round(cost, 2)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

In the uncleaned dataset, there were 207,023 Bay Wheels rides in the dataset with 13 columns (ride_id, rideable_type, started_at, ended_at, start_station_name, start_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_id, start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng, member_casual). Of the 13 columns, 4 are float data types and 9 are object data types.

In the cleaned dataset, there are 202,655 Bay Wheels rides in the dataset with 19 columns (ride_id, bike_type, started_at, ended_at, ride_duration, start_station_name, start_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_id, start_lat, start_lng, end_lat, end_lng, rider_type, start_datehour, end_date_hour, start_dayofweek, end_dayofweek, dist_in_km, est_ride_cost). Of these 19 columns, 7 are float data types, 2 are integer data types, 2 are datetime data types, 4 are categorical data types and 5 are object data types.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in when the most trips are taken in terms of time of day and day of the week, the duration of the trips and how it might vary with the type of membership or the type of bike. I am also curious as to whether the distance between starting and ending latitude/longitudes has any correlation to these variables. Finally, I am curious about the estimated cost per ride.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The start and end times of the rides (start_datehour, end_datehour, start_dayofweek, end_dayofweek), the bike type (bike_type), the membership type (rider_type), the distance (dist_in_km) and the estimated cost of a ride (est_ride_cost).

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The ride_duration, dist_in_kim and est_ride_cost variables took on a large range of values, so I looked at the data using a log transform. Under the transformation, the data looked roughly unimodal for ride_duration and dist_in_kim but not for est_ride_cost.

There were more rides by casual riders than by members in August 2021.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I wanted to know more about the time and day of the week for rides. To do this I had to manipulate the date/time data in the dataset. Once I converted the start_at and ended_at values to datetime objects and pulled out the start hour, end hour and day of the week for rides, I think it was unusual that more rides were on Sunday and Tuesday, even though the most common hours of the day for starting a ride was during what is generally considered to be rush hour. I also created values for ride duration (in minutes), distance between latitude/longitude points (in kilometers) and estimated cost for a ride.

During my exploration I found outlier values (negative ride durations and ride durations of zero), which I dropped from the dataset. I also found rides where the end_lat values were null and the rides were days long. These are likely to be lost or stolen bikes and were dropped from the dataset as well. Also, I substituted the string "Unavailable" where the start or end station was null because I wanted to be able to chart the top 10 start and end stations and to get a better visual sense of how much data was missing.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The most common start times for rides varied depending on whether it was a weekday (where the start times all shared a certain pattern with spikes in the morning and rush hour) or a weekend (where the start times peaked between roughly noon to 4 pm). Casual (non-member) riders are predominant on the weekends. Also, more electric bikes than classic bikes are ridden on weekdays and weekends, and members ride more classic bikes than casual riders.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

That more members and casual riders rode electric bikes instead of classic bikes and that the median ride duration in minutes (except for a few outliers) for both electric and classic bikes are similar. Also, on a daily basis, the ride patterns are different for casual riders vs. members. The number of rides by casual riders tend to peak on Saturdays and appear to be lowest on Mondays. By comparison, members tend to ride during the weekday, with ridership dropping on Saturdays and dropping to their lowest on Sundays.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Overall, Bay Wheels are ridden for relatively short "final mile" trips that average a little more than a mile and take 15-20 minutes. More rides were by casual riders on electric bikes and they tended to ride on weekends. Members tended to ride on weekdays and not on weekends, which suggests that members ride Bay Wheels are part of a regular commute to and from downtown SF. Member rides during the weekday showed two peaks, one during morning rush hour and one during late afternoon/early evening rush hour; casual rides during the weekday showed one peak during late afternoon/early evening rush hour(5 p.m.). And even though it is a point-to-point estimate, the mean estimated ride distance was farther for both casual riders and members on electric bikes than on classic bikes, which makes sense if you need to get somewhere without sweating.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Given that we are in a pandemic and people are still working remotely, I am not surprised that overall, member ridership is lower than casual ridership. I was surprised, however, that casual ridership peaks on the weekends. Also, I was surprised that the mean ride duration for members were similar on both weekdays and weekends, even though members take fewer rides on the weekends. Finally, I was surprised that the mean estimated ride distance on docked bikes was shorter than for electric bikes, even though the mean ride duration is longer for docked bikes.
